metadata.title: Evektor SportStar
aws::graph::propositions: Evektor SportStar Aircraft Technical Specifications
The Evektor SportStar is powered by a single Rotax 912ULS air-cooled piston engine.
The Rotax 912ULS engine typically drives a three-bladed VZLU V230C variable-pitch propeller.
Alternative fixed-pitch propellers can be fitted to the Evektor SportStar.
Alternative variable-pitch propellers can be fitted to the Evektor SportStar.
The Rotax 912ULS engine can be operated using automotive-standard unleaded petrol.
The Rotax 912ULS engine can use avgas for limited periods if required.
The Rotax 912ULS engine can use mogas for limited periods if required.
A push/pull throttle lever is the primary engine control in the Evektor SportStar.
The throttle lever is centrally mounted in the base of the instrument panel.
The throttle lever incorporates a twist function to make fine adjustments to the engine's rpm without moving the lever.
The twist function in the throttle lever is uncommon.
A centrally located propeller lever is mounted on the cockpit floor.
The propeller lever is used to adjust the pitch of the propeller.
Electrical power in the Evektor SportStar is provided by the engine's integrated generator.
The integrated generator charges a single 12V battery.
The Evektor SportStar is of mostly-metal construction.
The Evektor SportStar is primarily made of anodized aluminum.
The aluminum used in the Evektor SportStar is corrosion-proofed.
A limited amount of composite materials are used in the Evektor SportStar.
Composite materials are used in areas such as panels in the Evektor SportStar.

text:
The aircraft is powered by a single Rotax 912ULS air-cooled piston engine, which typically drives a three-bladed VZLU V230C variable-pitch propeller, although alternative fixed- or variable-pitch propellers can be fitted. This engine can be operated using automotive-standard unleaded petrol; avgas and mogas can also be used for limited periods if required. A push/pull throttle lever is the primary engine control, this being centrally mounted in the base of the instrument panel; it incorporates an uncommon twist function to make fine adjustments to the engine's rpm without moving the lever. A centrally located propeller lever mounted on the cockpit floor is used to adjust the pitch of the propeller. Electrical power is provided by the engine's integrated generator that charges a single 12V battery.
The SportStar is of mostly-metal construction, being primarily made of anodized, corrosion-proofed aluminum; a limited amount of composite materials are used in areas such as panels.
